<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="398" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[2072,2666,851,1274]" lastBlockId="11.[1457,2665,1280,2416]" pageId="11" pageNumber="398">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2072,2349,1044,1077]" pageId="11" pageNumber="398">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 24.-5-33 cm, tail 10.5-13 cm; no specific data are available for body weight, but probably more than 500 g. Has uniformly chocolate-brown dorsal and ventral fur, except for a variably sized pure white patch on chest. Hindfoot is relatively short and broad, and snout extremely elongate. As in species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1842" box="[1557,1703,1327,1352]" class="Mammalia" family="Peramelidae" genus="Echymipera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Peramelemorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="398" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Echymipera</taxonomicName>
, incisor I 5 is absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="398" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[1457,2665,1280,2416]" pageId="11" pageNumber="398">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1460,1571,1359,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="398">Habitat.</emphasis>
Upper montane tropical forest. Notes made by collectors of all known specimens of this species state that animals were captured in “very precipitous jungle-clad limestone country” and in “heavy jungle, precipitous limestone terrain.” One collection label notes that specimen was taken at 6000 ft (c¢.1800 m).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
